					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Rep=
lacing a number with a simpler value</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For other us=
es, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding_(disambiguation)"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect mw-disambig" title=3D"Rounding (disambiguation)">Roun=
ding (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wi=
kipedia/commons/8/8a/Comparison_rounding_graphs_SMIL.svg"><img resource=3D"=
/wiki/File:Comparison_rounding_graphs_SMIL.svg" src=3D"https://upload.wikim=
edia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Comparison_rounding_graphs_SMIL.svg/3=
30px-Comparison_rounding_graphs_SMIL.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"3=
00" height=3D"300" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-f=
ile-height=3D"512"></a><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Compar=
ison_rounding_graphs_SMIL.svg" class=3D"mw-file-magnify"></a><figcaption><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_of_a_function" title=3D"Graph =
of a function">Graphs</a> of the result, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span>, of rounding <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> using different methods. For clarity,=
 the graphs are shown displaced from integer <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span> values. In the SVG file, hover over a =
method to highlight it and, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syn=
chronized_Multimedia_Integration_Language" title=3D"Synchronized Multimedia=
 Integration Language">SMIL</a>-enabled browsers, click to select or desele=
ct it.</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Rounding</b> or <b>rounding off</b> is the process of adjusting a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number" title=3D"Number">number</a> t=
o an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Approximate" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Approximate">approximate</a>, more convenient value, often w=
ith a shorter or simpler representation. For example, replacing $23.4476 wi=
th $23.45, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fraction" title=3D"=
Fraction">fraction</a> 312/937 with 1/3, or the expression =E2=88=9A2 with =
1.414.
</p><p>Rounding is often done to obtain a value that is easier to report an=
d communicate than the original. Rounding can also be important to avoid <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/False_precision" title=3D"False prec=
ision">misleadingly precise</a> reporting of a computed number, measurement=
, or estimate; for example, a quantity that was computed as 123456 but is k=
nown to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accuracy_and_precision"=
 title=3D"Accuracy and precision">accurate</a> only to within a few hundred=
 units is usually better stated as "about 123500".
</p><p>On the other hand, rounding of exact numbers will introduce some <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Round-off_error" title=3D"Round-off e=
rror">round-off error</a> in the reported result. Rounding is almost unavoi=
dable when reporting many computations =E2=80=93 especially when <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_(mathematics)" title=3D"Division (m=
athematics)">dividing</a> two numbers in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integer</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Fixed-point_arithmetic" title=3D"Fixed-point arithmetic">fix=
ed-point arithmetic</a>; when computing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Mathematical_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematical fu=
nction">mathematical functions</a> such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Square_root" title=3D"Square root">square roots</a>, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logarithm" title=3D"Logarithm">logarithms</a>, =
and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sine" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Sine">sines</a>; or when using a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Floating-point_arithmetic" title=3D"Floating-point arithmetic">floati=
ng-point</a> representation with a fixed number of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures" title=3D"Significant figures">signifi=
cant digits</a>. In a sequence of calculations, these rounding errors gener=
ally <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propagation_of_uncertainty" t=
itle=3D"Propagation of uncertainty">accumulate</a>, and in certain <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ill-conditioned" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Ill-conditioned">ill-conditioned</a> cases they may make the result =
meaningless.
</p><p>Accurate rounding of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transc=
endental_function" title=3D"Transcendental function">transcendental mathema=
tical functions</a> is difficult because the number of extra digits that ne=
ed to be calculated to resolve whether to round up or down cannot be known =
in advance. This problem is known as "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Rounding#Table-maker's_dilemma">the table-maker's dilemma</a>".
</p><p>Rounding has many similarities to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Quantization_(signal_processing)" title=3D"Quantization (signal =
processing)">quantization</a> that occurs when <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Physical_quantity" title=3D"Physical quantity">physical quanti=
ties</a> must be encoded by numbers or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Digital_signal_(signal_processing)" title=3D"Digital signal (signal pr=
ocessing)">digital signals</a>.
</p><p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Approximately_equals_sign=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Approximately equals sign">wavy equals sig=
n</a> (<big><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E2%89%88" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"=E2=89=88">=E2=89=88</a></b></big>, <i>approximately=
 equal to</i>) is sometimes used to indicate rounding of exact numbers, e.g=
. 9.98 =E2=89=88 10. This sign was introduced by <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Alfred_George_Greenhill" title=3D"Alfred George Greenhill">A=
lfred George Greenhill</a> in 1892.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-1"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>Ideal characteristics of rounding methods include:
</p>
<ol><li>Rounding should be done by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">function</a>. T=
his way, when the same input is rounded in different instances, the output =
is unchanged.</li>
<li>Calculations done with rounding should be close to those done without r=
ounding.
<ul><li>As a result of (1) and (2), the output from rounding should be clos=
e to its input, often as close as possible by some <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Metric_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Metri=
c (mathematics)">metric</a>.</li></ul></li>
<li>To be considered rounding, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Range_of_a_function" title=3D"Range of a function">range</a> will be a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subset" title=3D"Subset">subset</a> o=
f the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain_of_a_function" title=
=3D"Domain of a function">domain</a>, often <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Discrete_set" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Discrete set">discre=
te</a>. A classical range is the integers, <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">Z</a></b>.</li>
<li>Rounding should preserve <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symme=
try_in_mathematics" title=3D"Symmetry in mathematics">symmetries</a> that a=
lready exist between the domain and range. With finite precision (or a disc=
rete domain), this translates to removing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Bias_(statistics)" title=3D"Bias (statistics)">bias</a>.</li>
<li>A rounding method should have utility in computer science or human arit=
hmetic where finite precision is used, and speed is a consideration.</li></=
ol>
<p>Because it is not usually possible for a method to satisfy all ideal cha=
racteristics, many different rounding methods exist.
</p><p>As a general rule, rounding is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Idempotence" title=3D"Idempotence">idempotent</a>;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cit=
e_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> i.e., once a number has been rounded, rounding it agai=
n to the same precision will not change its value. Rounding functions are a=
lso <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monotonic_function" title=3D"M=
onotonic function">monotonic</a>; i.e., rounding two numbers to the same ab=
solute precision will not exchange their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Inequality_(mathematics)" title=3D"Inequality (mathematics)">order</=
a> (but may give the same value). In the general case of a discrete range, =
they are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piecewise_constant_functi=
on" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Piecewise constant function">piecewise c=
onstant functions</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Types_of_rounding">Types of=
 rounding</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRo=
unding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Types of r=
ounding"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
