<p>For example, 23.5 gets rounded to 24, and =E2=88=9223.5 gets rounded to =
=E2=88=9224.
</p><p>This can be more efficient on computers that use <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sign-magnitude" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sign-m=
agnitude">sign-magnitude</a> representation for the values to be rounded, b=
ecause only the first omitted digit needs to be considered to determine if =
it rounds up or down. This is one method used when rounding to <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures" title=3D"Significant figu=
res">significant figures</a> due to its simplicity.
</p><p>This method, also known as <b>commercial rounding</b>,<sup class=3D"=
noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"=
Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to re=
liable sources. (November 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> trea=
ts positive and negative values symmetrically, and therefore is free of ove=
rall positive/negative bias if the original numbers are positive or negativ=
e with equal probability. It does, however, still have bias away from zero.
</p><p>It is often used for currency conversions and price roundings (when =
the amount is first converted into the smallest significant subdivision of =
the currency, such as cents of a euro) as it is easy to explain by just con=
sidering the first fractional digit, independently of supplementary precisi=
on digits or sign of the amount (for strict equivalence between the paying =
and recipient of the amount).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Rounding_half_to_even">Roun=
ding half to even</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: R=
ounding half to even"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>One may also <b>round half to even</b>, a tie-breaking rule without posi=
tive/negative bias <i>and</i> without bias toward/away from zero. By this c=
onvention, if the fractional part of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">x</span> is 0.5, then <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" styl=
e=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span> is the even integer nearest to <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>. Thus, for example=
, 23.5 becomes 24, as does 24.5; however, =E2=88=9223.5 becomes =E2=88=9224=
, as does =E2=88=9224.5. This function minimizes the expected error when su=
mming over rounded figures, even when the inputs are mostly positive or mos=
tly negative, provided they are neither mostly even nor mostly odd.
</p><p>This variant of the round-to-nearest method is also called <b>conver=
gent rounding</b>, <b>statistician's rounding</b>, <b>Dutch rounding</b>, <=
b>Gaussian rounding</b>, <b>odd=E2=80=93even rounding</b>,<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding=
#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> or <b>bankers' rounding</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite=
_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>This is the default rounding mode used in <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/IEEE_754" title=3D"IEEE 754">IEEE 754</a> operations for res=
ults in binary floating-point formats.
</p><p>By eliminating bias, repeated addition or subtraction of independent=
 numbers, as in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_walk#One-=
dimensional_random_walk" title=3D"Random walk">one-dimensional random walk<=
/a>, will give a rounded result with an error that tends to grow in proport=
ion to the square root of the number of operations rather than linearly.
</p><p><span class=3D"cleanup-needed-content" style=3D"padding-left:0.1em; =
padding-right:0.1em; color:var(--color-subtle, #54595d); border:1px solid v=
ar(--border-color-subtle, #c8ccd1);">However, this rule distorts the distri=
bution by increasing the probability of evens relative to odds. That is why=
 this rule is for situations where sums are more important than distributio=
n.</span><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em;=
 white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedi=
a:Please_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"What is=
 the distribution? (Certainly not a uniform distribution, because the measu=
re of the set of the halfway cases is zero, thus these cases would have no =
influence.) And what does &quot;where sums are more important than distribu=
tion&quot; mean? (October 2025)">clarification needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Rounding_half_to_odd">Round=
ing half to odd</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Rou=
nding half to odd"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p>One may also <b>round half to odd</b>, a similar tie-breaking rule to ro=
und half to even. In this approach, if the fractional part of <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> is 0.5, then <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span> is the odd int=
eger nearest to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x=
</span>. Thus, for example, 23.5 becomes 23, as does 22.5; while =E2=88=922=
3.5 becomes =E2=88=9223, as does =E2=88=9222.5.
</p><p>This method is also free from positive/negative bias and bias toward=
/away from zero, provided the numbers to be rounded are neither mostly even=
 nor mostly odd.  It also shares the round half to even property of distort=
ing the original distribution, as it increases the probability of odds rela=
tive to evens. It was the method used for bank balances in the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom" title=3D"United Kingdom">Unite=
d Kingdom</a> when it decimalized its currency<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-=
9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.=
1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiki=
pedia:Please_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"Nee=
ds a complete reference. (May 2023)">clarification needed</span></a></i>]</=
sup>.
</p><p>This variant is almost never used in computations, except in situati=
ons where one wants to avoid increasing the scale of floating-point numbers=
, which have a limited exponent range. With <i>round half to even</i>, a no=
n-infinite number would round to infinity, and a small <em><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denormal" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Denormal"=
>denormal</a></em> value would round to a normal non-zero value. Effectivel=
y, this mode prefers preserving the existing scale of tie numbers, avoiding=
 out-of-range results when possible for numeral systems of even <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix" title=3D"Radix">radix</a> (such as bin=
ary and decimal).<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-lef=
t:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D=
"The ''problem'' would be avoided only for halfway numbers. So, how can thi=
s be useful in practice? Any practical example? (September 2017)">clarifica=
tion needed</span></a> (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Talk:R=
ounding#Round_half_to_odd" title=3D"Talk:Rounding">talk</a>)</i>]</sup>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rounding_to_prepare_for_sho=
rter_precision">Rounding to prepare for shorter precision</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Rounding to prepare for shorter p=
recision"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<p>This rounding mode is used to avoid getting a potentially wrong result a=
fter <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#Double_rounding">mul=
tiple roundings</a>. This can be achieved if all roundings except the final=
 one are done using rounding to prepare for shorter precision ("RPSP"), and=
 only the final rounding uses the externally requested mode.
</p><p>With decimal arithmetic, final digits of 0 and 5 are avoided; if the=
re is a choice between numbers with the least significant digit 0 or 1, 4 o=
r 5, 5 or 6, 9 or 0, then the digit different from 0 or 5 shall be selected=
; otherwise, the choice is arbitrary. IBM defines that, in the latter case,=
 a digit with the smaller magnitude shall be selected.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#ci=
te_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> RPSP can be applied with the step between two conseq=
uent roundings as small as a single digit (for example, rounding to 1/10 ca=
n be applied after rounding to 1/100).
For example, when rounding to integer,
</p>
<ul><li>20.0 is rounded to 20;</li>
<li>20.01, 20.1, 20.9, 20.99, 21, 21.01, 21.9, 21.99 are rounded to 21 (avo=
iding a final 0);</li>
<li>22.0, 22.1, 22.9, 22.99 are rounded to 22;</li>
<li>24.0, 24.1, 24.9, 24.99 are rounded to 24 (avoiding a final 5);</li>
<li>25.0 is rounded to 25;</li>
<li>25.01, 25.1 are rounded to 26 (avoiding a final 5).</li></ul>
<p>In the example from "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#D=
ouble_rounding">Double rounding</a>" section, rounding 9.46 to one decimal =
gives 9.4, which rounding to integer in turn gives 9.
</p><p>With binary arithmetic, this rounding is also called "round to odd" =
(not to be confused with "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding=
#Rounding_half_to_odd">round half to odd</a>"). For example, when rounding =
to 1/4 (0.01 in binary),
</p>
<ul><li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D 2.0</span> =E2=87=92 result is=
 2 (10.00 in binary)</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml">2.0 &lt; <i>x</i> &lt; 2.5</span> =E2=87=92 res=
ult is 2.25 (10.01 in binary)</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D 2.5</span> =E2=87=92 result is 2.5=
 (10.10 in binary)</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml">2.5 &lt; <i>x</i> &lt; 3.0</span> =E2=87=92 res=
ult is 2.75 (10.11 in binary)</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D 3.0</span> =E2=87=92 result is 3 (=
11.00 in binary)</li></ul>
<p>For correct results with binary arithmetic, each rounding step must remo=
ve at least 2 binary digits, otherwise, wrong results may appear. For examp=
le,
</p>
<ul><li>3.125 RPSP to 1/4 =E2=87=92 result is 3.25</li>
<li>3.25 RPSP to 1/2 =E2=87=92 result is 3.5</li>
<li>3.5 round-half-to-even to 1 =E2=87=92 result is 4 (wrong)</li></ul>
<p>If the erroneous middle step is removed, the final rounding to integer r=
ounds 3.25 to the correct value of 3.
</p><p>RPSP is implemented in hardware in IBM <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/ZSeries" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"ZSeries">zSeries</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PSeries" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"PSeries">pSeries</a>. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
ython_(programming_language)" title=3D"Python (programming language)">Pytho=
n</a> module "Decimal", <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tcl" title=
=3D"Tcl">Tcl</a> module "math", <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ha=
skell" title=3D"Haskell">Haskell</a> package "decimal-arithmetic", and poss=
ibly others, this mode is called ROUND_05UP or round05up.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Randomized_rounding_to_an_i=
nteger">Randomized rounding to an integer</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" =
title=3D"Edit section: Randomized rounding to an integer"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Alternating_tie-breaking">A=
lternating tie-breaking</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Alternating tie-breaking"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>One method, more obscure than most, is to alternate direction when round=
ing a number with 0.5 fractional part. All others are rounded to the closes=
t integer. Whenever the fractional part is 0.5, alternate rounding up or do=
wn: for the first occurrence of a 0.5 fractional part, round up, for the se=
cond occurrence, round down, and so on. Alternatively, the first 0.5 fracti=
onal part rounding can be determined by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Random_seed" title=3D"Random seed">random seed</a>.  "Up" and "down=
" can be any two rounding methods that oppose each other - toward and away =
from positive infinity or toward and away from zero.
</p><p>If occurrences of 0.5 fractional parts occur significantly more than=
 a restart of the occurrence "counting", then it is effectively bias free. =
With guaranteed zero bias, it is useful if the numbers are to be summed or =
averaged.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Random_tie-breaking">Random=
 tie-breaking</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Rand=
om tie-breaking"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<p>If the fractional part of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">x</span> is 0.5, choose <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">y</span> randomly between <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</=
i> + 0.5</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=92 0.5</span>, =
with equal probability. All others are rounded to the closest integer.
</p><p>Like round-half-to-even and round-half-to-odd, this rule is essentia=
lly free of overall bias, but it is also fair among even and odd <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span> values. An advanta=
ge over alternate tie-breaking is that the last direction of rounding on th=
e 0.5 fractional part does not have to be "remembered".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Stochastic_rounding">Stocha=
stic rounding</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Stoc=
hastic rounding"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<p>Rounding as follows to one of the closest integer toward negative infini=
ty and the closest integer toward positive infinity, with a probability dep=
endent on the proximity is called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Stochastic" title=3D"Stochastic">stochastic</a> rounding and will give an u=
nbiased result on average.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-stochastic_11-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-stochas=
tic-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \operatorname {Round} (x)=3D{\begin{cases}\lfloor x\rfloor &amp;{\text{ w=
ith probability }}1-(x-\lfloor x\rfloor )=3D\lfloor x\rfloor -x+1\\[5mu]\lf=
loor x\rfloor +1&amp;{\text{ with probability }}{x-\lfloor x\rfloor }\end{c=
ases}}}">
