-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.671ex; width:70.696ex; height:6.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \o=
peratorname {Round} (x)=3D{\begin{cases}\lfloor x\rfloor &amp;{\text{ with =
probability }}1-(x-\lfloor x\rfloor )=3D\lfloor x\rfloor -x+1\\[5mu]\lfloor=
 x\rfloor +1&amp;{\text{ with probability }}{x-\lfloor x\rfloor }\end{cases=
}}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>For example, 1.6 would be rounded to 1 with probability 0.4 and to 2 wit=
h probability 0.6.
</p><p>Stochastic rounding can be accurate in a way that a rounding <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function=
 (mathematics)">function</a> can never be. For example, suppose one started=
 with 0 and added 0.3 to that one hundred times while rounding the running =
total between every addition. The result would be 0 with regular rounding, =
but with stochastic rounding, the expected result would be 30, which is the=
 same value obtained without rounding. This can be useful in <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_learning" title=3D"Machine learning">mac=
hine learning</a> where the training may use low precision arithmetic itera=
tively.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-stochastic_11-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-stochastic-11"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Stochastic rounding is also a way to achieve 1-dimensional <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dithering" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ditheri=
ng">dithering</a>.
</p>
