<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Rounding_to_other_values">R=
ounding to other values</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Rounding to other values"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rounding_to_a_specified_mul=
tiple">Rounding to a specified multiple</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Rounding to a specified multiple"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The most common type of rounding is to round to an integer; or, more gen=
erally, to an integer multiple of some increment =E2=80=93 such as rounding=
 to whole tenths of seconds, hundredths of a dollar, to whole multiples of =
1/2 or 1/8=E2=80=AFinch, to whole dozens or thousands, etc.
</p><p>In general, rounding a number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">x</span> to a multiple of some specified positive value=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> entails=
 the following steps:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \mathrm {roundToMultiple} (x,m)=3D\mathrm {round} (x/m)\times m}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">r</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">o</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">u</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">n</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">d</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">T</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">o</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">M</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">u</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">l</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">t</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">i</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">p</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">l</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">e</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>m</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">r</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">o</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">u</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">n</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">d</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>m</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=C3=97<!-- =C3=97 --></mo>
        <mi>m</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathrm {roun=
dToMultiple} (x,m)=3D\mathrm {round} (x/m)\times m}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c4db72375183e0263551cc5d2f3d6a2a9bb0c123" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:43.872ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \m=
athrm {roundToMultiple} (x,m)=3D\mathrm {round} (x/m)\times m}"></span></dd=
></dl>
<p>For example, rounding <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =3D 2.1784</span>=
 dollars to whole cents (i.e., to a multiple of 0.01) entails computing <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml">2.1784 / 0.01 =3D 217.84</span>, then rounding that to=
 218, and finally computing <span class=3D"texhtml">218 =C3=97 0.01 =3D 2.1=
8</span>.
</p><p>When rounding to a predetermined number of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures" title=3D"Significant figures">signific=
ant digits</a>, the increment <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">m</span> depends on the magnitude of the number to be rounded =
(or of the rounded result).
</p><p>The increment <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">m</span> is normally a finite fraction in whatever <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numeral_system" title=3D"Numeral system">numeral syste=
m</a> is used to represent the numbers. For display to humans, that usually=
 means the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal" title=3D"Decim=
al">decimal numeral system</a> (that is, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> is an integer times a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Po=
wer (mathematics)">power</a> of 10, like 1/1000 or 25/100). For intermediat=
e values stored in digital computers, it often means the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_number" title=3D"Binary number">binary numera=
l system</a> (<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</=
span> is an integer times a power of 2).
</p><p>The abstract single-argument "round()" function that returns an inte=
ger from an arbitrary real value has at least a dozen distinct concrete def=
initions presented in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding=
#Rounding_to_integer">rounding to integer</a> section. The abstract two-arg=
ument "roundToMultiple()" function is formally defined here, but in many ca=
ses it is used with the implicit value <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i> =3D=
 1</span> for the increment and then reduces to the equivalent abstract sin=
gle-argument function, with also the same dozen distinct concrete definitio=
ns.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Logarithmic_rounding">Logar=
ithmic rounding</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section: Log=
arithmic rounding"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Rounding_to_a_specified_pow=
er">Rounding to a specified power</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D=
"Edit section: Rounding to a specified power"><span>edit</span></a><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Rounding to a specified <i>power</i> is very different from rounding to =
a specified <i>multiple</i>; for example, it is common in computing to need=
 to round a number to a whole power of 2. The steps, in general, to round a=
 positive number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
x</span> to a power of some positive number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> other than 1, are:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \mathrm {roundToPower} (x,b)=3Db^{\mathrm {round} (\log _{b}x)},x&gt;0,b&=
gt;0,b\neq 1}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">r</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">o</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">u</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">n</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">d</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">T</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">o</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">P</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">o</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">w</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">e</mi>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">r</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msup>
          <mi>b</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">r</mi>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">o</mi>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">u</mi>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">n</mi>
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">d</mi>
            </mrow>
            <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
            <msub>
              <mi>log</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi>b</mi>
              </mrow>
            </msub>
            <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
            <mi>x</mi>
            <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>&gt;</mo>
        <mn>0</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo>&gt;</mo>
        <mn>0</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>b</mi>
        <mo>=E2=89=A0<!-- =E2=89=A0 --></mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathrm {roun=
dToPower} (x,b)=3Db^{\mathrm {round} (\log _{b}x)},x&gt;0,b&gt;0,b\neq 1}</=
annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/a7feafadb7b7e2ae802ad577722d6891adf76fba" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:53.521ex; height:3.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \m=
athrm {roundToPower} (x,b)=3Db^{\mathrm {round} (\log _{b}x)},x&gt;0,b&gt;0=
,b\neq 1}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Many of the caveats applicable to rounding to a multiple are applicable =
to rounding to a power.
</p><p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromatic_scale" tit=
le=3D"Chromatic scale">chromatic "twelve-tone" scale</a> of music, <span cl=
ass=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">3</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</sp=
an></span> is rounded to <span class=3D"texhtml">2<sup>7/12</sup></span> (a=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_fifth" title=3D"Perfect f=
ifth">fifth</a>), <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-dat=
a:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">4</s=
pan>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">3</span></span> is rounded to <span class=
=3D"texhtml">2<sup>5/12</sup></span> (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Perfect_fourth" title=3D"Perfect fourth">fourth</a>), <link rel=3D"mw=
-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><sp=
an class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">5</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">=
4</span></span> is rounded to <span class=3D"texhtml">2<sup>4/12</sup></spa=
n> (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_third" title=3D"Major =
third">major third</a>), <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D=
"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"nu=
m">6</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">5</span></span> is rounded to <span=
 class=3D"texhtml">2<sup>3/12</sup></span> (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Minor_third" title=3D"Minor third">minor third</a>), and <link =
rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r115494=
1027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">9</span>=E2=81=84<span class=
=3D"den">8</span></span> is rounded to <span class=3D"texhtml">2<sup>2/12</=
sup></span> (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diminished_third" t=
itle=3D"Diminished third">diminished third</a>).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Scaled_rounding">Scaled rou=
nding</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoundi=
ng&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Scaled roundi=
ng"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>This type of rounding, which is also named <b>rounding to a logarithmic =
scale</b>, is a variant of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roundin=
g#Rounding_to_a_specified_power">rounding to a specified power</a>. Roundin=
g on a logarithmic scale is accomplished by taking the log of the amount an=
d doing normal rounding to the nearest value on the log scale.
</p><p>For example, resistors are supplied with <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Preferred_number" title=3D"Preferred number">preferred number=
s</a> on a logarithmic scale. In particular, for resistors with a 10% accur=
acy, they are supplied with nominal values 100, 120, 150, 180, 220, etc. ro=
unded to multiples of 10 (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E12_seri=
es" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"E12 series">E12 series</a>). If a calcul=
ation indicates a resistor of 165 ohms is required then <span class=3D"texh=
tml">log(150) =3D 2.176</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">log(165) =3D 2.217<=
/span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">log(180) =3D 2.255</span>. The logarithm=
 of 165 is closer to the logarithm of 180 therefore a 180 ohm resistor woul=
d be the first choice if there are no other considerations.
</p><p>Whether a value <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>x</i> =E2=88=88 (<i>a</i>=
, <i>b</i>)</span> rounds to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">a</span> or <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">b</span> depends upon whether the squared value <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>x</i><sup>2</sup></span> is greater than or less than the product <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>ab</i></span>. The value 165 rounds to 180 in the =
resistors example because <span class=3D"texhtml">165<sup>2</sup> =3D 27225=
</span> is greater than <span class=3D"texhtml">150 =C3=97 180 =3D 27000</s=
pan>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Floating-point_rounding">Fl=
oating-point rounding</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Floating-point rounding"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floating-point_arithmetic" t=
itle=3D"Floating-point arithmetic">floating-point arithmetic</a>, rounding =
aims to turn a given value <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">x</span> into a value <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">y</span> with a specified number of <em>significant</em> dig=
its. In other words, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">y</span> should be a multiple of a number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> that depends on the magnitude of <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>. The number =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> is a pow=
er of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix" title=3D"Radix">b=
ase</a> (usually 2 or 10) of the floating-point representation.
</p><p>Apart from this detail, all the variants of rounding discussed above=
 apply to the rounding of floating-point numbers as well. The algorithm for=
 such rounding is presented in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Rounding#Scaled_rounding">Scaled rounding</a> section above, but with a co=
nstant scaling factor <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i> =3D 1</span>, and an=
 integer base <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i> &gt; 1</span>.
</p><p>Where the rounded result would overflow the result for a directed ro=
unding is either the appropriate signed infinity when "rounding away from z=
ero", or the highest representable positive finite number (or the lowest re=
presentable negative finite number if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">x</span> is negative), when "rounding toward zero". Th=
e result of an overflow for the usual case of <i>round to nearest</i> is al=
ways the appropriate infinity.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rounding_to_a_simple_fracti=
on">Rounding to a simple fraction</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D=
"Edit section: Rounding to a simple fraction"><span>edit</span></a><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In some contexts it is desirable to round a given number <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> to a "neat" fraction =
=E2=80=93 that is, the nearest fraction <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i> =
=3D <i>m</i>/<i>n</i></span> whose numerator <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> and denominator <span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> do not exceed a given maximum.=
 This problem is fairly distinct from that of rounding a value to a fixed n=
umber of decimal or binary digits, or to a multiple of a given unit <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span>. This problem i=
s related to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Farey_sequence" title=
=3D"Farey sequence">Farey sequences</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Stern%E2%80%93Brocot_tree" title=3D"Stern=E2=80=93Brocot tree">S=
tern=E2=80=93Brocot tree</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Continued_fraction" title=3D"Continued fraction">continued fractions</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rounding_to_an_available_va=
lue">Rounding to an available value</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=
=3D"Edit section: Rounding to an available value"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Finished <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lumber" title=3D"Lumbe=
r">lumber</a>, writing paper, electronic components, and many other product=
s are usually sold in only a few standard values.
</p><p>Many design procedures describe how to calculate an approximate valu=
e, and then "round" to some standard size using phrases such as "round down=
 to nearest standard value", "round up to nearest standard value", or "roun=
d to nearest standard value".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-12"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>When a set of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Preferred_val=
ue" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Preferred value">preferred values</a> is=
 equally spaced on a logarithmic scale, choosing the closest <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Preferred_value" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Preferred value">preferred value</a> to any given value can be seen as a fo=
rm of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#Scaled_rounding">sc=
aled rounding</a>. Such rounded values can be directly calculated.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Rounding#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Arbitrary_bins">Arbitrary b=
ins</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRounding=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: Arbitrary bins"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>More general rounding rules can separate values at arbitrary break point=
s, used for example in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_binnin=
g" title=3D"Data binning">data binning</a>. A related mathematically formal=
ized tool is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signpost_sequence" ti=
tle=3D"Signpost sequence">signpost sequences</a>, which use notions of dist=
ance other than the simple difference =E2=80=93 for example, a sequence may=
 round to the integer with the smallest <i>relative</i> (percent) error.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Rounding_in_other_contexts"=
>Rounding in other contexts</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit=
 section: Rounding in other contexts"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Dithering_and_error_diffusi=
on">Dithering and error diffusion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D=
"Edit section: Dithering and error diffusion"><span>edit</span></a><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>When digitizing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_sign=
al" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Continuous signal">continuous signals</a=
>, such as sound waves, the overall effect of a number of measurements is m=
ore important than the accuracy of each individual measurement. In these ci=
rcumstances, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dithering" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Dithering">dithering</a>, and a related technique, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Error_diffusion" title=3D"Error diffu=
sion">error diffusion</a>, are normally used. A related technique called <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulse-width_modulation" title=3D"Pul=
se-width modulation">pulse-width modulation</a> is used to achieve analog t=
ype output from an inertial device by rapidly pulsing the power with a vari=
able duty cycle. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delta-sigma_modul=
ation" title=3D"Delta-sigma modulation">Delta-sigma modulation</a> is commo=
nly used for converting between real-world signals and digital signals, whi=
ch allows control of the frequency statistics of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Quantization_(signal_processing)" title=3D"Quantization (sig=
nal processing)">Quantization_(signal_processing)</a>.
</p><p>Error diffusion tries to ensure the error, on average, is minimized.=
 When dealing with a gentle slope from one to zero, the output would be zer=
o for the first few terms until the sum of the error and the current value =
becomes greater than 0.5, in which case a 1 is output and the difference su=
btracted from the error so far. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fl=
oyd%E2%80%93Steinberg_dithering" title=3D"Floyd=E2=80=93Steinberg dithering=
">Floyd=E2=80=93Steinberg dithering</a> is a popular error diffusion proced=
ure when digitizing images.
</p><p>As a one-dimensional example, suppose the numbers <span class=3D"tex=
html">0.9677</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">0.9204</span>, <span class=3D"=
texhtml">0.7451</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml">0.3091</span> occur in =
order and each is to be rounded to a multiple of <span class=3D"texhtml">0.=
01</span>. In this case the cumulative sums, <span class=3D"texhtml">0.9677=
</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">1.8881 =3D 0.9677 + 0.9204</span>, <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml">2.6332 =3D 0.9677 + 0.9204 + 0.7451</span>, and <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml">2.9423 =3D 0.9677 + 0.9204 + 0.7451 + 0.3091</span>, are each=
 rounded to a multiple of <span class=3D"texhtml">0.01</span>: <span class=
=3D"texhtml">0.97</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">1.89</span>, <span class=
=3D"texhtml">2.63</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml">2.94</span>. The firs=
t of these and the differences of adjacent values give the desired rounded =
values: <span class=3D"texhtml">0.97</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">0.92 =
=3D 1.89 =E2=88=92 0.97</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">0.74 =3D 2.63 =E2=
=88=92 1.89</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml">0.31 =3D 2.94 =E2=88=92 2.6=
3</span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Monte_Carlo_arithmetic">Mon=
te Carlo arithmetic</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Monte Carlo arithmetic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Monte Carlo arithmetic is a technique in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_method" title=3D"Monte Carlo method">Monte Carlo meth=
ods</a> where the rounding is randomly up or down. Stochastic rounding can =
be used for Monte Carlo arithmetic, but in general, just rounding up or dow=
n with equal probability is more often used. Repeated runs will give a rand=
om distribution of results which can indicate the stability of the computat=
ion.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Exact_computation_with_roun=
ded_arithmetic">Exact computation with rounded arithmetic</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D33" title=3D"Edit section: Exact computation with rounded ar=
ithmetic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<p>It is possible to use rounded arithmetic to evaluate the exact value of =
a function with integer domain and range. For example, if an integer <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is known to be=
 a perfect square, its square root can be computed by converting <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> to a floating-poin=
t value <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">z</span>,=
 computing the approximate square root <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">z</span> with floating point, and then rounding <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> to the nearest i=
nteger <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span>. =
If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is no=
t too big, the floating-point round-off error in <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> will be less than 0.5, so the roun=
ded value <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">y</span=
> will be the exact square root of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">n</span>. This is essentially why <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Slide_rule" title=3D"Slide rule">slide rules</a> could be=
 used for exact arithmetic.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Double_rounding">Double rou=
nding</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRoundi=
ng&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D34" title=3D"Edit section: Double roundi=
ng"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Sticky_rounding"></span><span class=3D"anch=
or" id=3D"Rounding_to_odd"></span>
Rounding a number twice in succession to different levels of precision, wit=
h the latter precision being coarser, is not guaranteed to give the same re=
sult as rounding once to the final precision except in the case of directed=
 rounding.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NB_Double_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-NB_Double-16"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>nb 2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> For instance rounding 9.46 to one decimal gives 9.5, and then 10 when=
 rounding to integer using rounding half to even, but would give 9 when rou=
nded to integer directly. Borman and Chatfield<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-=
17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> discuss the implications of double rounding when comparing =
data rounded to one decimal place to specification limits expressed using i=
ntegers.
</p><p>In <i>Martinez v. Allstate</i> and <i>Sendejo v. Farmers</i>, litiga=
ted between 1995 and 1997, the insurance companies argued that double round=
ing premiums was permissible and in fact required. The US courts ruled agai=
nst the insurance companies and ordered them to adopt rules to ensure singl=
e rounding.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some computer languages and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/IEEE_754-2008_revision" title=3D"IEEE 754-2008 revision">IEEE 754-2008=
</a> standard dictate that in straightforward calculations the result shoul=
d not be rounded twice. This has been a particular problem with Java as it =
is designed to be run identically on different machines, special programmin=
g tricks have had to be used to achieve this with <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/X87" title=3D"X87">x87</a> floating point.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roundin=
g#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The=
 Java language was changed to allow different results where the difference =
does not matter and require a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stri=
ctfp" title=3D"Strictfp">strictfp</a> qualifier to be used when the results=
 have to conform accurately; strict floating point has been restored in Jav=
a&nbsp;17.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In some algorithms, an intermediate result is computed in a larger p=
recision, then must be rounded to the final precision. Double rounding can =
be avoided by choosing an adequate rounding for the intermediate computatio=
n. This consists in avoiding to round to midpoints for the final rounding (=
except when the midpoint is exact). In binary arithmetic, the idea is to ro=
und the result toward zero, and set the least significant bit to 1 if the r=
ounded result is inexact; this rounding is called <i>sticky rounding</i>.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Equivalently, it consists in ret=
urning the intermediate result when it is exactly representable, and the ne=
arest floating-point number with an odd significand otherwise; this is why =
it is also known as <i>rounding to odd</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-23"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A concrete impleme=
ntation of this approach, for binary and decimal arithmetic, is implemented=
 as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#Rounding_to_prepare_f=
or_shorter_precision">Rounding to prepare for shorter precision</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Table-maker's_dilemma"><spa=
n id=3D"Table-maker.27s_dilemma"></span>Table-maker's dilemma</h3><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedi=
t&amp;section=3D35" title=3D"Edit section: Table-maker's dilemma"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_M._Kahan" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"William M. Kahan">William M. Kahan</a> coined the term "T=
he Table-Maker's Dilemma" for the unknown cost of rounding <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcendental_function" title=3D"Transcendental f=
unction">transcendental functions</a>:
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>Nobody knows how much it would cost =
to compute <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i><sup><i>w</i></sup></span> corre=
ctly rounded for <em>every</em> two floating-point arguments at which it do=
es not over/underflow. Instead, reputable math libraries compute elementary=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcendental_function" title=3D=
"Transcendental function">transcendental functions</a> mostly within slight=
ly more than half an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_in_the_l=
ast_place" title=3D"Unit in the last place">ulp</a> and almost always well =
within one ulp. Why can't <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i><sup><i>w</i></su=
p></span> be rounded within half an ulp like SQRT? Because nobody knows how=
 much computation it would cost... No general way exists to predict how man=
y extra digits will have to be carried to compute a transcendental expressi=
on and round it <em>correctly</em> to some preassigned number of digits. Ev=
en the fact (if true) that a finite number of extra digits will ultimately =
suffice may be a deep theorem.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-25"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
</p></blockquote>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_754" title=3D"IEEE 754=
">IEEE 754</a> floating-point standard guarantees that add, subtract, multi=
ply, divide, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fused_multiply%E2%80%=
93add" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fused multiply=E2=80=93add">fused mul=
tiply=E2=80=93add</a>, square root, and floating-point remainder will give =
the correctly rounded result of the infinite-precision operation. No such g=
uarantee was given in the 1985 standard for more complex functions and they=
 are typically only accurate to within the last bit at best. However, the 2=
008 standard guarantees that conforming implementations will give correctly=
 rounded results which respect the active rounding mode; implementation of =
the functions, however, is optional.
</p><p>Using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gelfond%E2%80%93S=
chneider_theorem" title=3D"Gelfond=E2=80=93Schneider theorem">Gelfond=E2=80=
=93Schneider theorem</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linde=
mann%E2%80%93Weierstrass_theorem" title=3D"Lindemann=E2=80=93Weierstrass th=
eorem">Lindemann=E2=80=93Weierstrass theorem</a>, many of the standard elem=
entary functions can be proved to return <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Transcendental_number" title=3D"Transcendental number">transcendenta=
l</a> results, except on some well-known arguments; therefore, from a theor=
etical point of view, it is always possible to correctly round such functio=
ns. However, for an implementation of such a function, determining a limit =
for a given precision on how accurate results need to be computed, before a=
 correctly rounded result can be guaranteed, may demand a lot of computatio=
n time or may be out of reach.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Muller_2010_26-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-=
Muller_2010-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> In practice, when this limit is not known (or o=
nly a very large bound is known), some decision has to be made in the imple=
mentation (see below); but according to a probabilistic model, correct roun=
ding can be satisfied with a very high probability when using an intermedia=
te accuracy of up to twice the number of digits of the target format plus s=
ome small constant (after taking special cases into account).
</p><p>Some programming packages offer correct rounding. The <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU_MPFR" title=3D"GNU MPFR">GNU MPFR</a> packag=
e gives correctly rounded arbitrary precision results. Some other libraries=
 implement elementary functions with correct rounding in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double-precision_floating-point_format#IEEE_754_doub=
le-precision_binary_floating-point_format:_binary64" title=3D"Double-precis=
ion floating-point format">IEEE 754 double precision</a> (binary64):
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IBM" title=3D"IBM">IBM</a>=
's <i>ml4j</i>, which stands for <i>Mathematical Library for Java</i>, writ=
ten by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abraham_Ziv" title=3D"Abrah=
am Ziv">Abraham Ziv</a> and Moshe Olshansky in 1999, correctly rounded to n=
earest only.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#=
cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> This library was claimed to be portable, but only=
 binaries for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PowerPC" title=3D"Po=
werPC">PowerPC</a>/<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IBM_AIX" title=
=3D"IBM AIX">AIX</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SPARC" title=
=3D"SPARC">SPARC</a>/<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oracle_Solari=
s" title=3D"Oracle Solaris">Solaris</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/X86" title=3D"X86">x86</a>/<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Windows_NT" title=3D"Windows NT">Windows NT</a> were provided. According=
 to its documentation, this library uses a first step with an accuracy a bi=
t larger than double precision, a second step based on <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double-double_arithmetic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Double-double arithmetic">double-double arithmetic</a>, and a third ste=
p with a 768-bit precision based on arrays of IEEE 754 double-precision flo=
ating-point numbers.</li>
<li>IBM's <i>Accurate portable mathematical library</i> (abbreviated as APM=
athLib or just MathLib),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=
