e-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Rounding#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> also called libultim,<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roundi=
ng#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> in rounding to nearest only. This library uses=
 up to 768 bits of working precision. It was included in the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU_C_Library" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"GN=
U C Library">GNU C Library</a> in 2001,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-32"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> but the "slow paths" (providing correct rounding) were removed fro=
m 2018 to 2021.</li>
<li>CRlibm, written in the old Ar=C3=A9naire team (LIP, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ENS_Lyon" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"ENS Lyon">EN=
S Lyon</a>), first distributed in 2003.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-33"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> It supports the 4 rounding modes and is proved, using the knowledg=
e of the hardest-to-round cases.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-34"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> More efficient than IBM MathL=
ib.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-coremath-ieee29_36-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-coremath-ieee29-36"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> Succeeded by Metalibm (2014), which automates the formal proofs.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sun_Microsystems" title=3D"Sun=
 Microsystems">Sun Microsystems</a>'s libmcr of 2004, in the 4 rounding mod=
es.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note=
-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> For the difficult cases, this library also uses multiple p=
recision, and the number of words is increased by 2 each time the Table-mak=
er's dilemma occurs (with undefined behavior in the very unlikely event tha=
t some limit of the machine is reached).</li>
<li>The CORE-MATH project (2022) provides some correctly rounded functions =
in the 4 rounding modes for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X86-64=
