n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-coremath-ieee29-36"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li=
>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LLVM" title=3D"LLVM">LLVM</a> =
libc provides some correctly rounded functions in the 4 rounding modes.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>There exist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computable_number" =
title=3D"Computable number">computable numbers</a> for which a rounded valu=
e can never be determined no matter how many digits are calculated. Specifi=
c instances cannot be given but this follows from the undecidability of the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halting_problem" title=3D"Halting=
 problem">halting problem</a>. For instance, if <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Goldbach%27s_conjecture" title=3D"Goldbach's conjecture">Gold=
bach's conjecture</a> is true but <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Unprovable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Unprovable">unprovable</a>, then=
 the result of rounding the following value, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Rounding#Rounding_up">up to the next integer</a> cannot be determined: =
either <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>=
=3D1+10<sup>=E2=88=92<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">k</span></sup> where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">k</span> is the first even number greater than 4 which is not the s=
um of two primes, or <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">n</span>=3D1 if there is no such number. The rounded result is 2 if suc=
h a number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</spa=
n> exists and 1 otherwise. The value before rounding can however be approxi=
mated to any given precision even if the conjecture is unprovable.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Interaction_with_string_sea=
rches">Interaction with string searches</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D36" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Interaction with string searches"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Rounding can adversely affect a string search for a number. For example,=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span> ro=
unded to four digits is "3.1416" but a simple search for this string will n=
ot discover "3.14159" or any other value of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span> rounded to more than four digits. =
In contrast, truncation does not suffer from this problem; for example, a s=
imple string search for "3.1415", which is <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span> truncated to four digits, will disc=
over values of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
=CF=80</span> truncated to more than four digits.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D37" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The concept of rounding is very old, perhaps older than the concept of d=
ivision itself. Some ancient <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clay_=
tablet" title=3D"Clay tablet">clay tablets</a> found in <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesopotamia" title=3D"Mesopotamia">Mesopotamia</a> co=
ntain tables with rounded values of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Multiplicative_inverse" title=3D"Multiplicative inverse">reciprocals</a> =
and square roots in base 60.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-42"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Rounded approximations to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pi" titl=
e=3D"Pi"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</=
span></a>, the length of the year, and the length of the month are also anc=
ient=E2=80=94see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sexagesimal#Examp=
les" title=3D"Sexagesimal">base 60 examples</a>.
</p><p>The <i>round-half-to-even</i> method has served as <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Standards_Association" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"American Standards Association">American Standard</a> Z25.1 and=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASTM" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"ASTM">ASTM</a> standard E-29 since 1940.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-=
43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> The origin of the terms <i>unbiased rounding</i> and <i>sta=
tistician's rounding</i> are fairly self-explanatory. In the 1906 fourth ed=
ition of <i>Probability and Theory of Errors</i> <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Robert_Simpson_Woodward" title=3D"Robert Simpson Woodward">R=
obert Simpson Woodward</a> called this "the computer's rule",<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roun=
ding#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> indicating that it was then in common use by=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_computer" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Human computer">human computers</a> who calculated mathematic=
al tables. For example, it was recommended in <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Simon_Newcomb" title=3D"Simon Newcomb">Simon Newcomb</a>'s c. 1=
882 book <i>Logarithmic and Other Mathematical Tables</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roundin=
g#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Lucius Tuttle's 1916 <i>Theory of Measurements<=
/i> called it a "universally adopted rule" for recording physical measureme=
nts.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Churchill_Eisenhart" title=3D"Churchill Eisenhart">Churchill=
 Eisenhart</a> indicated the practice was already "well established" in dat=
a analysis by the 1940s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The origin of the term <i>bankers' rounding</i> remains more obscure=
. If this rounding method was ever a standard in banking, the evidence has =
proved extremely difficult to find. To the contrary, section 2 of the Europ=
ean Commission report <i>The Introduction of the Euro and the Rounding of C=
urrency Amounts</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> suggests th=
at there had previously been no standard approach to rounding in banking; a=
nd it specifies that "half-way" amounts should be rounded up.
</p><p>Until the 1980s, the rounding method used in floating-point computer=
 arithmetic was usually fixed by the hardware, poorly documented, inconsist=
ent, and different for each brand and model of computer. This situation cha=
nged after the IEEE 754 floating-point standard was adopted by most compute=
r manufacturers. The standard allows the user to choose among several round=
ing modes, and in each case specifies precisely how the results should be r=
ounded. These features made numerical computations more predictable and mac=
hine-independent, and made possible the efficient and consistent implementa=
tion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interval_arithmetic" title=
=3D"Interval arithmetic">interval arithmetic</a>.
</p><p>Currently, much research tends to round to multiples of 5 or 2. For =
example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C3%B6rg_Baten" title=3D=
"J=C3=B6rg Baten">J=C3=B6rg Baten</a> used <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Age_heaping" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Age heaping">age heapi=
ng</a> in many studies, to evaluate the numeracy level of ancient populatio=
ns. He came up with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whipple%27=
s_index#ABCC_Index" title=3D"Whipple's index">ABCC Index</a>, which enables=
 the comparison of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numeracy" t=
itle=3D"Numeracy">numeracy</a> among regions possible without any historica=
l sources where the population <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lit=
eracy" title=3D"Literacy">literacy</a> was measured.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite=
_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Rounding_functions_in_progr=
amming_languages">Rounding functions in programming languages</h2><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedi=
t&amp;section=3D38" title=3D"Edit section: Rounding functions in programmin=
g languages"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p>Most <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language" titl=
e=3D"Programming language">programming languages</a> provide functions or s=
pecial syntax to round fractional numbers in various ways. The earliest num=
eric languages, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fortran" t=
itle=3D"Fortran">Fortran</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
_(programming_language)" title=3D"C (programming language)">C</a>, would pr=
ovide only one method, usually truncation (toward zero). This default metho=
d could be implied in certain contexts, such as when assigning a fractional=
 number to an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_(computer_sc=
ience)" title=3D"Integer (computer science)">integer</a> <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variable_(programming)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Variable (programming)">variable</a>, or using a fractional number as a=
n index of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Array_data_type" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Array data type">array</a>. Other kinds of roun=
ding had to be programmed explicitly; for example, rounding a positive numb=
er to the nearest integer could be implemented by adding 0.5 and truncating=
.
</p><p>In the last decades, however, the syntax and the standard <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Library_(computing)" title=3D"Library (compu=
ting)">libraries</a> of most languages have commonly provided at least the =
four basic rounding functions (up, down, to nearest, and toward zero). The =
tie-breaking method can vary depending on the language and version or might=
 be selectable by the programmer. Several languages follow the lead of the =
IEEE 754 floating-point standard, and define these functions as taking a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double-precision_floating-point_form=
at" title=3D"Double-precision floating-point format">double-precision float=
</a> argument and returning the result of the same type, which then may be =
converted to an integer if necessary. This approach may avoid spurious <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_overflow" title=3D"Integer ove=
rflow">overflows</a> because floating-point types have a larger range than =
integer types. Some languages, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/PHP" title=3D"PHP">PHP</a>, provide functions that round a value to a =
specified number of decimal digits (e.g., from 4321.5678 to 4321.57 or 4300=
). In addition, many languages provide a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Printf" title=3D"Printf">printf</a> or similar string formatting fun=
ction, which allows one to convert a fractional number to a string, rounded=
 to a user-specified number of decimal places (the <i>precision</i>). On th=
e other hand, truncation (round to zero) is still the default rounding meth=
od used by many languages, especially for the division of two integer value=
s.
</p><p>In contrast, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cascading_Styl=
e_Sheets" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalable_Vector_Graphics" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Scalable Vector Graphics">SVG</a> do not define a=
ny specific maximum precision for numbers and measurements, which they trea=
t and expose in their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Document_Obj=
ect_Model" title=3D"Document Object Model">DOM</a> and in their <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interface_description_language" title=3D"Inte=
rface description language">IDL</a> interface as strings as if they had <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_RAM" title=3D"Real RAM">infinite=
 precision</a>, and do not discriminate between integers and floating-point=
 values; however, the implementations of these languages will typically con=
vert these numbers into IEEE 754 double-precision floating-point values bef=
ore exposing the computed digits with a limited precision (notably within s=
tandard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaScript" title=3D"JavaS=
cript">JavaScript</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ECMAScrip=
t" title=3D"ECMAScript">ECMAScript</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-50"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
