<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Other_rounding_standards">O=
ther rounding standards</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D39" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Other rounding standards"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Some disciplines or institutions have issued standards or directives for=
 rounding.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"US_weather_observations">US=
 weather observations</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D40" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: US weather observations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In a guideline issued in mid-1966,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rounding#cite_note-51"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States" title=3D=
"United States">U.S.</a> Office of the Federal Coordinator for Meteorology =
determined that weather data should be rounded to the nearest round number,=
 with the "round half up" tie-breaking rule. For example, 1.5 rounded to in=
teger should become 2, and =E2=88=921.5 should become =E2=88=921. Prior to =
that date, the tie-breaking rule was "round half away from zero".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Negative_zero_in_meteorolog=
y">Negative zero in meteorology</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DRounding&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D41" title=3D"E=
dit section: Negative zero in meteorology"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signed_zero#In_round=
ed_values_such_as_temperatures" title=3D"Signed zero">Signed zero =C2=A7&nb=
sp;In rounded values such as temperatures</a></div>
<p>Some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meteorologist" title=3D"Me=
teorologist">meteorologists</a> may write "=E2=88=920" to indicate a temper=
ature between 0.0 and =E2=88=920.5 degrees (exclusive) that was rounded to =
an integer. This notation is used when the negative sign is considered impo=
rtant, no matter how small is the magnitude; for example, when rounding tem=
peratures in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celsius" title=3D=
"Celsius">Celsius</a> scale, where below zero indicates freezing.<sup class=
=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=
=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references t=
o reliable sources. (July 2009)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
